node.text:
“It makes sense that every aspect of a deVOL Kitchen, right down to the handles, should be equally well designed and made. Good design is all about equal consideration for every aspect, form, aesthetic, utility etc. The quality of deVOL is in their attention to detail, the last finishing touches.” - Stephanie O'Leary, deVOL's jeweller and metalsmith. 
#deVOLKitchens

node.title: How we make deVOL handcrafted kitchen handles...

node.text: We did an Instagram story a few months ago now, it was a little behind the scenes look into the @devolceramics studio and a brand new product that we were experimenting with and developing. We always show you the finished products but there's talented people working and being inventive and creative every single day at our Cotes Mill studios, so we love to try and show you as much of the making process as possible. We did a little vote in the story and nearly all of you said you'd like to see these tiles be added as a permanent product to our tile range... so here's a little update! They're not totally ready yet but Hannah is almost there... using our new (but very old!!) tile press and imprinting some of her grandma's vintage lace, she has created the loveliest glossy, Victorian inspired tiles in rich shades of burgundy and blue and pink and brown. As soon as the final tiles are complete and colours and shapes are chosen and they're up on the website we'll let you know, but for now, we hope you enjoy this video of Hannah in action! #deVOLKitchens

node.title: In The Studio: making vintage lace tiles

node.text: Have a little look around @pearllowe's fairytale home and one of our most-loved kitchens ever!! This is eclectic English eccentricity at its very best. A little bit romantic, a little bit edgy and totally unique - we love Pearl's style and feel very lucky to have been able to work with her on this dream of a kitchen. What's your favourite part? #deVOLKitchens

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by deVOL Kitchens on August 20, 2021 tagging @the.history.keeper. May be an image of indoor.

node.text: Happy Friday everyone! We thought we'd share one of our favourites this evening. Did anyone spot this in the first episode of For the Love of Kitchens? It's a place you really have to see to believe, a moated medieval house with wrought iron gates and fallow deer and acres of parkland. You can just see a little hint of the impressive grounds and fabulous arched windows reflected in these glazed doors. We love seeing these old favourites brought to life on film and you get to meet the lovely owner @the.history.keeper too, what a treat. #deVOLKitchens

node.text: A new episode of our TV show 'For the Love of Kitchens' is out!! If you're in the US or the UK you can watch it now on @magnolianetwork on discovery+. This week we're whisking you away to St Ives with @devolpaul and @hapdesigns as we take on the renovation of our little deVOL seaside cottage and create a sunny kitchen using furniture from an old showroom display. We watch our amazing MD, Robin, handcraft the very first deVOL Gaselier Light and we visit style icon @pearllowe and her husband, Danny, in beautiful Somerset for a look around their breathtaking home and our most-loved deVOL kitchen of all time. Ok, we know we've said every episode is the best one yet but this is such a gooden. As always, we cannot wait to hear what you think... this TV stuff doesn't get any less nerve-wracking as the weeks go on!! Swipe for a little look at the new episode... #deVOLKitchens #MagnoliaNetwork #ForTheLoveOfKitchens

node.text: Honed or polished marble? It's a question that always comes up in our design appointments and here on our Instagram. There's no right or wrong but understanding the differences will make decision making easier. Aesthetically, polished is more luxe and glamorous, and honed is more understated. In terms of durability, polishing the surface of your marble adds a layer of protection, so for things like red wine spills, the substance is less likely to completely penetrate and stain the surface if it’s polished compared to honed. A honed finish is slightly better at hiding scratches, but these will still be visible no matter the finish you choose. With acidic substances like lemon juice or vinegar, a honed finish will hold up better. If you spill lemon juice on a polished marble it will cause etchings and ultimately take away the shiny effect, leaving a slightly matt patch. We tend to go for a honed finish more often than not but sometimes a space just calls for a little extra glamour and nothing but polished will do! #deVOLKitchens

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by deVOL Kitchens in York, England. May be an image of kitchen.

node.text: Our Classic English furniture is bespoke, which means it's all made especially for you, so it makes sense for you to be able to choose your own colours too. We have a really good range of deVOL shades that we love and feel are well suited to our furniture, to current tastes and classic tastes, but we understand the excitement, importance and difficulty of choosing the right colours, so if we haven't got what you're looking for we will happily mix you up your perfect shade. Colour can be daunting, it can keep you awake with its possibilities!! But it can give you the opportunity to create your dreams, so go for it and make your kitchen fabulous. #deVOLKitchens

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by deVOL Kitchens in deVOL Kitchens. May be an image of chandelier, table and indoor.

node.text: Big tables, low lighting, subtle warm colours and a sense of being cosseted by familiar and beautiful things, that's what we love to see. Less of the gadgets and more of the real life comforts, a good place to bake bread and make big pots of soup and best of all, somewhere for everybody you love to sit and feel comfy, to be together. #deVOLKitchens

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by deVOL Kitchens in Leicestershire. May be an image of indoor.

node.text: We thought you'd like to see this image this morning just because it's beautiful and we love how these savvy customers achieved it... the worktops are old scaffolding planks that have been sanded down and oiled and the taps were found discarded in the garden, with a little love they're good as new. Kitchen projects cost a lot of money, so do try and be resourceful, reuse and recycle where you can, get creative and remember you don't need to update absolutely everything all in one big, expensive hurry. #deVOLKitchens

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by deVOL Kitchens on August 18, 2021. May be an image of kitchen and brick wall.

node.text: An evening in this deVOL kitchen and utility room in beautiful Balham, sounds good to us. The owners had only moved in a month before our photoshoot but when we turned up, it was like they had lived there for years. So comfortable and so stylish but in an uncontrived way which can be really hard to achieve. Their wish for this room was for it to be sociable, comfortable, stand the test of time style-wise and take a great deal of use. With a little help from us, they did it and we hope they're still loving the room 6 years on, we certainly are. #deVOLKitchens

node.text: You don't often see this big bank of cabinetry in our photos of the Millhouse scullery but it's integral to the whole design. A beautifully roomy pantry ready to store every ingredient and kitcheny thing you would ever need, and an integrated fridge, so the rest of the space can remain enviably simple. The little gap between the cupboard and the ceiling is a key deVOL look and helps the substantial piece feel a little more freestanding and elegant and classic. #deVOLKitchens

node.text: We chose an extra special edging for the worktops in our St. John's Square showroom. This profile style is called 'Ogee' and we went for it because this room is really quite grand and we wanted the worktop to be a little more ornate than the usual square edge we have always done. It has a wonderfully tactile and historic and glamorous feel and takes the honed black granite to a whole new level. You can get away with this edging on most hard, dense stones but marble is a bit risky. #deVOLKitchens

node.text: Pearl has an exceptional eye for making a room look casually amazing, delightful things old and new, textiles, quirky unusual objects, collections and essentials, all looking so good. But this kitchen isn't just about looks, @pearllowe's ability to acknowledge every aspect of a room’s function and not just make it look good, well that's serious talent. Our Shaker cupboards work so well here because they're very simple, very well-made and very easy to dress up or down and style just as you like. #deVOLKitchens

node.text: People have fallen in love with our Haberdasher's wall cupboards, all slim and elegant and oozing mid-century style. They're beautifully made, all the detail is in the bespoke hinges and the stained oak frames, leaving you with a simple and sophisticated look. We've even been incorporating these cupboards into Shaker and Sebastian Cox kitchens and the mix is really good. #deVOLKitchens

node.text:
They say when you know, you know... and that's exactly what the owners felt when they walked into this Victorian brownstone in New Jersey. In fact, this was actually the very first home they went to view, some places just have that magical power, don't they - you step inside and you can picture the life you will live there, it just feels right. The owners fell hard for the original features in this old house, they went to painstaking lengths to salvage the crown moulding that wraps around the top of the kitchen, even recreating it in places to match the original 1850s plaster. It's just the best when we get to work with people who care about beautiful interiors as much as we do, what a fantastic kitchen this is. #deVOLKitchens

Thank you to @and.studio.interiors for letting us share your incredible home with all our followers and to @nicole_franzen for the beautiful photographs.
